Actually all you have to do is to cut required numbers from the generated string.

```java
public static String getEsignConfirmNum(int length) {
    SecureRandom random = new SecureRandom();
    StringBuilder buf = new StringBuilder(2 * length);

    while (buf.length() &lt; length) {
        buf.append(random.nextInt(1_000_000));
    }

    return buf.substring(0, length);
}
```

But, on the other side all you need just convert the number to the `String` and add missing `0` as a prefix.
```java
public static String getEsignConfirmNum(int bound) {
    SecureRandom random = new SecureRandom();
    int width = String.valueOf(bound).length();
    int num = random.nextInt(bound);
    return String.format(&quot;%0&quot; + width + &#39;d&#39;, num);
}
```

Another way is just generate required amount of one-digit numbers:
```java
public static String getEsignConfirmNum(int length) {
    SecureRandom random = new SecureRandom();
    StringBuilder buf = new StringBuilder(length);

    for (int i = 0; i &lt; length; i++)
        buf.append(random.nextInt(10));

    return buf.toString();
}
```

