answers.body_markdown:
&gt;It is composed of key(e.g Rank or Hits) and value(e.g A or 1).

I’m going to assume these are the only two keys.  If there are more, it is possible to make the layout more flexible.  If there could be a lot of them, a JTable may be a more appropriate choice.

&gt;Its cells&#39; width is not same and fixed.

GridBagLayout is designed for that exact case.  It’s powerful and flexible, but that creates a potential for complexity, so it is somewhat hard to use properly.

&gt;Text in every cell can be selected and copy.

For now, based on your follow-up comment, I’m going to set aside this requirement, as the text and appearance are easier to accomplish with JLabels, whose text cannot be selected.

First, you’ll want variables to hold all your cells.  Some of them might not need to be kept in private instance fields, if they never change, but I didn’t want to make that assumption.

    public class SpecSheet {
        private final JLabel baseDamageField;

        private final JLabel rankLabelField;
        private final JLabel rankValueField;

        private final JLabel noblePhantasmTypeLabelField;
        private final JLabel noblePhantasmTypeValueField;

        private final JLabel hitsLabelField;
        private final JLabel hitsValueField;

        private final JLabel perHitPercentageLabelField;
        private final JLabel perHitPercentageValueField;

        private final JLabel effectLabelField;
        private final JLabel effectValueField;

        private final JLabel npLevelLabelField;
        private final JLabel[] npLevelNameFields;

        private final JLabel npLevelDamageLabelField;
        private final JLabel[] npLevelDamageValueFields;

        private final JLabel overchargeEffectLabelField;
        private final JLabel overchargeEffectValueField;

        private final JLabel chargeLabelField;
        private final JLabel[] chargeNameFields;

        private final JLabel chargeNPLabelField;
        private final JLabel[] chargeNPValueFields;

        private final JFrame frame;

Then we can define them:

    public SpecSheet() {
        baseDamageField = new JLabel(&quot; Base Damage: x1.5 &quot;);
        baseDamageField.setIcon(new ImageIcon(
            SpecSheet.class.getResource(&quot;buster.png&quot;)));
        baseDamageField.setHorizontalTextPosition(JLabel.CENTER);
        baseDamageField.setVerticalTextPosition(JLabel.BOTTOM);

        rankLabelField = new JLabel(&quot;Rank&quot;);
        rankValueField = new JLabel(&quot;A&quot;);

        noblePhantasmTypeLabelField = new JLabel(&quot;Noble Phantasm Type&quot;);
        noblePhantasmTypeValueField = new JLabel(&quot;Anti-Fortress&quot;);

        hitsLabelField = new JLabel(&quot;Hits&quot;);
        hitsValueField = new JLabel(&quot; 1 &quot;);

        perHitPercentageLabelField = new JLabel(&quot;Per Hit Percentage&quot;);
        perHitPercentageValueField = new JLabel(&quot;100%&quot;);

        effectLabelField = new JLabel(&quot;Effect&quot;);
        effectValueField = new JLabel(&quot;Deals damage to all enemies.&quot;);
        effectValueField.setIcon(new ImageIcon(
            SpecSheet.class.getResource(&quot;increase.png&quot;)));
        effectValueField.setHorizontalTextPosition(JLabel.LEADING);

        npLevelLabelField = new JLabel(&quot;NP Level&quot;);
        npLevelNameFields = new JLabel[] {
            new JLabel(&quot;1&quot;),
            new JLabel(&quot;2&quot;),
            new JLabel(&quot;3&quot;),
            new JLabel(&quot;4&quot;),
            new JLabel(&quot;5&quot;),
        };

        npLevelDamageLabelField = new JLabel(&quot;Damage+&quot;);
        npLevelDamageLabelField.setIcon(
            new ImageIcon(SpecSheet.class.getResource(&quot;damage-boost.png&quot;)));
        npLevelDamageValueFields = new JLabel[] {
            new JLabel(&quot;300%&quot;),
            new JLabel(&quot;400%&quot;),
            new JLabel(&quot;450%&quot;),
            new JLabel(&quot;475%&quot;),
            new JLabel(&quot;500%&quot;),
        };

        overchargeEffectLabelField = new JLabel(&quot;Overcharge Effect&quot;);
        overchargeEffectValueField =
            new JLabel(&quot;Charges own NP gauge&quot;);

        chargeLabelField = new JLabel(&quot;Charge&quot;);
        chargeNameFields = new JLabel[] {
            new JLabel(&quot;100%&quot;),
            new JLabel(&quot;200%&quot;),
            new JLabel(&quot;300%&quot;),
            new JLabel(&quot;400%&quot;),
            new JLabel(&quot;500%&quot;),
        };

        chargeNPLabelField = new JLabel(&quot;NP+&quot;);
        chargeNPLabelField.setIcon(new ImageIcon(
            SpecSheet.class.getResource(&quot;np-boost.png&quot;)));
        chargeNPValueFields = new JLabel[] {
            new JLabel(&quot;20%&quot;),
            new JLabel(&quot;27.5%&quot;),
            new JLabel(&quot;35%&quot;),
            new JLabel(&quot;42.5%&quot;),
            new JLabel(&quot;50%&quot;),
        };

(Note: `SpecSheet.class.getResource` expects the image file to reside in the *same package* as the SpecSheet class itself.  This is by design;  you don’t want to place images in the root of an application, since that increases the chance they will conflict with something else in the classpath.)

Next, we want to set their appearance.  I found it cleaner to move that task into private methods:

    updateFonts();
    updateColors();
    updateBorders();

The methods are a bit painstaking, but you only have write them once:

    private void updateFonts() {
        JLabel[] boldLabelFields = {
            baseDamageField,
            rankLabelField,
            noblePhantasmTypeLabelField,
            hitsLabelField,
            perHitPercentageLabelField,
            effectLabelField,
            npLevelLabelField,
            npLevelDamageLabelField,
            overchargeEffectLabelField,
            chargeLabelField,
            chargeNPLabelField,
        };
        JLabel[][] boldFieldSets = {
            boldLabelFields,
            npLevelNameFields,
            chargeNameFields,
        };
        for (JLabel[] fieldSet : boldFieldSets) {
            for (JLabel field : fieldSet) {
                Font font = field.getFont();
                font = font.deriveFont(Font.BOLD);
                field.setFont(font);
            }
        }

        JLabel[] plainLabelFields = {
            rankValueField,
            noblePhantasmTypeValueField,
            hitsValueField,
            perHitPercentageValueField,
            overchargeEffectValueField,
        };
        JLabel[][] plainFieldSets = {
            plainLabelFields,
            npLevelDamageValueFields,
            chargeNPValueFields,
        };
        for (JLabel[] fieldSet : plainFieldSets) {
            for (JLabel field : fieldSet) {
                Font font = field.getFont();
                font = font.deriveFont(Font.PLAIN);
                field.setFont(font);
            }
        }
    }

Setting the colors:

    private void updateColors() {
        Color lightPink = Color.decode(&quot;#f6dde9&quot;);
        Color darkPink = Color.decode(&quot;#e5ccd8&quot;);

        Color lightGray = Color.decode(&quot;#ebebeb&quot;);
        Color darkGray = Color.decode(&quot;#dfdfdf&quot;);

        baseDamageField.setBackground(lightPink);
        overchargeEffectValueField.setBackground(lightPink);
        for (JLabel npField : chargeNPValueFields) {
            npField.setBackground(lightPink);
        }

        overchargeEffectLabelField.setBackground(darkPink);
        chargeLabelField.setBackground(darkPink);
        for (JLabel nameField : chargeNameFields) {
            nameField.setBackground(darkPink);
        }
        chargeNPLabelField.setBackground(darkPink);

        rankLabelField.setBackground(darkGray);
        noblePhantasmTypeLabelField.setBackground(darkGray);
        hitsLabelField.setBackground(darkGray);
        perHitPercentageLabelField.setBackground(darkGray);
        effectLabelField.setBackground(darkGray);
        npLevelLabelField.setBackground(darkGray);
        npLevelDamageLabelField.setBackground(darkGray);
        for (JLabel nameField : npLevelNameFields) {
            nameField.setBackground(darkGray);
        }

        rankValueField.setBackground(lightGray);
        noblePhantasmTypeValueField.setBackground(lightGray);
        hitsValueField.setBackground(lightGray);
        perHitPercentageValueField.setBackground(lightGray);
        effectValueField.setBackground(lightGray);
        for (JLabel valueField : npLevelDamageValueFields) {
            valueField.setBackground(lightGray);
        }
    }

And finally, the part you explicitly asked about—setting the borders:

    private void updateBorders() {
        Color borderColor = Color.decode(&quot;#bfbfbf&quot;);

        Border leftOnly =
            BorderFactory.createMatteBorder(0, 1, 0, 0, borderColor);
        rankLabelField.setBorder(leftOnly);
        noblePhantasmTypeLabelField.setBorder(leftOnly);

        Border topOnly =
            BorderFactory.createMatteBorder(1, 0, 0, 0, borderColor);
        chargeLabelField.setBorder(topOnly);
        effectLabelField.setBorder(topOnly);
        npLevelLabelField.setBorder(topOnly);
        npLevelDamageLabelField.setBorder(topOnly);
        overchargeEffectLabelField.setBorder(topOnly);
        chargeLabelField.setBorder(topOnly);
        chargeNPLabelField.setBorder(topOnly);

        Border leftAndTop =
            BorderFactory.createMatteBorder(1, 1, 0, 0, borderColor);
        rankValueField.setBorder(leftAndTop);
        noblePhantasmTypeValueField.setBorder(leftAndTop);
        hitsLabelField.setBorder(leftAndTop);
        hitsValueField.setBorder(leftAndTop);
        perHitPercentageLabelField.setBorder(leftAndTop);
        perHitPercentageValueField.setBorder(leftAndTop);
        effectValueField.setBorder(leftAndTop);
        npLevelLabelField.setBorder(leftAndTop);
        overchargeEffectValueField.setBorder(leftAndTop);
        for (JLabel field : npLevelNameFields) {
            field.setBorder(leftAndTop);
        }
        for (JLabel field : npLevelDamageValueFields) {
            field.setBorder(leftAndTop);
        }
        for (JLabel field : chargeNameFields) {
            field.setBorder(leftAndTop);
        }
        for (JLabel field : chargeNPValueFields) {
            field.setBorder(leftAndTop);
        }
    }

It’s a pain, but ultimately the method is only 40 lines long.

Going back to our constructor, we’re now ready to assemble everything:

    JPanel panel = new JPanel(new GridBagLayout());

    GridBagConstraints gbc = new GridBagConstraints();
    gbc.weightx = 1;
    gbc.weighty = 1;
    gbc.fill = GridBagConstraints.BOTH;
    gbc.ipadx = 40;
    gbc.ipady = 16;

    gbc.gridx = 0;
    gbc.gridy = 0;
    gbc.gridheight = 4;
    panel.add(baseDamageField, gbc);

    gbc.gridx++;
    gbc.gridheight = 1;
    panel.add(rankLabelField, gbc);
    gbc.gridy++;
    panel.add(rankValueField, gbc);
    gbc.gridy++;
    panel.add(hitsLabelField, gbc);
    gbc.gridy++;
    panel.add(hitsValueField, gbc);

    gbc.gridx++;
    gbc.gridy -= 3;
    gbc.gridwidth = 4;
    panel.add(noblePhantasmTypeLabelField, gbc);
    gbc.gridy++;
    panel.add(noblePhantasmTypeValueField, gbc);
    gbc.gridy++;
    panel.add(perHitPercentageLabelField, gbc);
    gbc.gridy++;
    panel.add(perHitPercentageValueField, gbc);

    gbc.gridx = 0;
    gbc.gridy++;
    gbc.gridwidth = 1;
    panel.add(effectLabelField, gbc);
    gbc.gridx++;
    gbc.gridwidth = GridBagConstraints.REMAINDER;
    panel.add(effectValueField, gbc);

    gbc.gridx = 0;
    gbc.gridy++;
    gbc.gridwidth = 1;
    panel.add(npLevelLabelField, gbc);
    for (JLabel nameField : npLevelNameFields) {
        gbc.gridx++;
        panel.add(nameField, gbc);
    }

    gbc.gridx = 0;
    gbc.gridy++;
    panel.add(npLevelDamageLabelField, gbc);
    for (JLabel valueField : npLevelDamageValueFields) {
        gbc.gridx++;
        panel.add(valueField, gbc);
    }

    gbc.gridx = 0;
    gbc.gridy++;
    panel.add(overchargeEffectLabelField, gbc);
    gbc.gridx++;
    gbc.gridwidth = GridBagConstraints.REMAINDER;
    panel.add(overchargeEffectValueField, gbc);

    gbc.gridx = 0;
    gbc.gridy++;
    gbc.gridwidth = 1;
    panel.add(chargeLabelField, gbc);
    for (JLabel nameField : chargeNameFields) {
        gbc.gridx++;
        panel.add(nameField, gbc);
    }

    gbc.gridx = 0;
    gbc.gridy++;
    panel.add(chargeNPLabelField, gbc);
    for (JLabel valueField : chargeNPValueFields) {
        gbc.gridx++;
        panel.add(valueField, gbc);
    }

    for (Object child : panel.getComponents()) {
        if (child instanceof JComponent c) {
            // Background colors are only used by opaque Swing components.
            c.setOpaque(true);
        }
        if (child instanceof JLabel label) {
            label.setHorizontalAlignment(JLabel.CENTER);
        }
    }

    frame = new JFrame(&quot;Sword of Promised Victory&quot;);
    frame.getContentPane().add(panel);
