Don&#39;t try to print it on the screen. Write it on the disk directly and check the PDF. Not sure how you got that content with corrupt characters, but it could be due to encoding issues while showing the bytes.
Since you have Base64 encoded PDF string, you don&#39;t have to convert it to `byte[]` too.  Directly pass it to `decode()` method.

```
String pdfB64 = &quot;&quot;;
FileOutputStream fos = new FileOutputStream(&quot;D:/Temp/test.pdf&quot;);
fos.write(Base64.getDecoder().decode(pdfB64));
fos.close();
```

I directly wrote the decoded bytes to the disk, and test.pdf opens up fine with &#39;TEST&#39; as text on the one-page PDF.

Update...

```
String pdfB64 = &quot;JVBERi0xL......JUVPRgo=&quot;;
byte[] pdfBytes = Base64.getDecoder().decode(pdfB64);
Charset ch = StandardCharsets.ISO_8859_1;
String pdfStr = new String(pdfBytes, ch);
System.out.println(pdfStr);  // This still shows corrupt, but that is due to CLI limitation
FileOutputStream fos = new FileOutputStream(&quot;D:/Temp/test.pdf&quot;);
fos.write(pdfStr.getBytes(ch));
fos.close();
```
Converting the `byte` array to string and back to the `byte` array using `ISO_8859_1` results in the same `byte` array in this sample case.
The file written on the disk is valid and opens up fine.
The only thing is both sides have to use the same charset for the conversion. So, the WSO2 side also has to have the option to use this charset to convert the received string to a `byte` array.

**BEST OPTION** would always be to pass Base64 encoded string and let the other side decode it and get the byte array, which can then be used as PDF content.

